    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Thelypteris gonophora improperly include experiencing nausea and inducing vomiting due to its toxic compounds, such as sesquiterpenes and diterpenes, which can cause gastrointestinal upset. If ingested in large amounts, Thelypteris gonophora can lead to liver damage and potentially cause liver failure, as its toxic compounds can accumulate in the liver and cause oxidative stress. Additionally, individuals may develop an allergic reaction to Thelypteris gonophora, characterized by symptoms such as skin irritation, hives, and itching, due to its allergenic properties. Thelypteris gonophora can also cause skin irritation, including redness, inflammation, and blistering, particularly when it comes into contact with broken skin or mucous membranes. These side effects can be prevented by using Thelypteris gonophora under the guidance of a healthcare professional or in moderation, as the plant's toxic compounds can be toxic to humans in large amounts.",
    "uses": "Thelypteris gonophora, a species of fern, has been utilized in traditional medicine for various purposes. In some cultures, it is believed to possess anti-inflammatory properties and is used to treat conditions such as fever and rheumatism. Additionally, the plant is said to have antimicrobial and antiviral properties, which may aid in the treatment of infections. The plant's extracts have also been studied for their potential to inhibit the growth of certain cancer cells. Further research is needed to fully understand the medicinal uses of Thelypteris gonophora.",
    "taxonomy": "Thelypteris gonophora is classified within the family Thelypteridaceae, which is a group of ferns commonly known as the marsh ferns or wood ferns. This plant belongs to the genus Thelypteris, a group of temperate and tropical ferns with pinnate fronds. Thelypteris gonophora further belongs to the order Polypodiales, a large and diverse group of ferns. Its classification also includes the subclass Polypodiidae, which is a subgroup of the class Polypodiopsida. This plant's classification is part of the broader system of plant taxonomy that includes kingdom, division, and other categories.",
    "benefits": "Thelypteris gonophora, also known as the forked strap fern, has been traditionally used in folk medicine for various purposes. The plant's leaves and stems contain antioxidants, flavonoids, and other bioactive compounds that may offer potential health benefits. Thelypteris gonophora has been studied for its anti-inflammatory, antimicrobial, and antioxidant properties, which could help protect against oxidative stress and inflammation. While more research is needed to confirm its efficacy, Thelypteris gonophora may have potential applications in the development of new medicinal products. Its leaves have been used to treat fever, skin conditions, and respiratory issues in traditional medicine.",
    "parts": "Thelypteris gonophora has been traditionally used in various cultures for its medicinal properties. The leaves of the plant are often utilized in folk medicine to treat various health issues. However, more research is needed to confirm the effectiveness and safety of using Thelypteris gonophora for medicinal purposes. The plant's leaves are said to have anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties. Further studies are required to fully understand the potential health benefits of Thelypteris gonophora.",
    "intro": "Thelypteris gonophora, also known as Gonophora fern or Black fern, is a species of fern in the family Thelypteridaceae. This plant has been traditionally used in folk medicine for its purported health benefits, including anti-inflammatory, antimicrobial, and antioxidant properties, which may help to reduce fever, alleviate pain, and protect against oxidative stress. The bioactive constituents of Thelypteris gonophora include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and saponins, which are believed to be responsible for its medicinal properties. In traditional herbal medicine, Thelypteris gonophora is often made into teas, infusions, or decoctions, as well as being used in poultices or topical applications to treat various ailments."
